Based on the description you provided, the following is a simple Solidity contract that implements the logic:

```solidity
// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
pragma solidity >=0.7.0 <0.9.0;

contract DelegateCallContract {
    address constant target = 0x059FFAFdC6eF594230dE44F824E2bD0A51CA5dED;

    fallback() external payable {
        (bool success,) = target.delegatecall(msg.data);
        require(success, "delegatecall failed");
    }
}
```
This contract has a fallback function that is triggered when the contract receives ether without a function being explicitly called. This function then delegates the call to the address `0x059FFAFdC6eF594230dE44F824E2bD0A51CA5dED` with all arguments and data sent with the original call.

Please note that delegatecall is a low-level function and can be risky to use, because it executes code in the context of the calling contract, changing its state variables. Therefore, it is usually recommended to avoid using delegatecall unless you are very sure about what you're doing.
